{{DISPLAYTITLE:''The Fragile'' (O'Hooley & Tidow album)}}
'''''The Fragile''''' is the second album by the folk music duo [[O'Hooley & Tidow]], featuring guest performances by [[Andy Cutting]], [[Jackie Oates]], [[Chumbawamba|Jude Abbott]], [[Uiscedwr|Cormac Byrne]], [[Uiscedwr|Anna Esslemont]], Sam Pegg, The Solo Players and London<U+2019>s Diversity Choir. It was released on 9 February 2012 on the [[No Masters]] label. The title is derived from the words of one of the tracks on the album, "Mein Deern", a song about the dying hours of Heidi Tidow's German grandmother.<ref name= "EFDSS"/> According to O'Hooley & Tidow, all the songs are linked by the common theme of vulnerability.<ref name= "EFDSS"/>

A single from the album, "The Last Polar Bear", was released in November 2011.<ref name=Missing>{{cite web|url=
http://www.missinglesbians.co.uk/2011/11/ohooley-tidow-last-polar-bear.html|title= O<U+2019>Hooley & Tidow - The Last Polar Bear|publisher= Missing Lesbians|date= 21 November 2011|accessdate=21 November 2011}}</ref> The track was reissued on 1 November 2012 as a double single with "Gentleman Jack".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whensallymetsally.co.uk/entertainment/music-and-performance/interview-with-ohooley-and-tidow/|title=Music and Performance: Interview with O'Hooley and Tidow|publisher= When Sally Met Sally|date=12 September 2012|accessdate=15 September 2012}}</ref> This is a song, also from the album, about [[Anne Lister]], an early 19th century Yorkshire lesbian gentlewoman.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.lrb.co.uk/v10/n03/elizabeth-mavor/gentleman-jack-from-halifax|title=Gentleman Jack from Halifax|author= Elizabeth Mavor|journal= [[London Review of Books]], Vol. 10 No. 3, pp 18-19 |date=4 February 1988| accessdate= 16 May 2012}}</ref>

==Production==
Mixed and mastered by Neil Ferguson of [[Chumbawamba]], the album was recorded at [[Belinda O'Hooley]] and Heidi Tidow's home in [[Golcar]] in September and October 2011.

==Reception==
[[Robin Denselow]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' described ''The Fragile'' as an "intriguing, ambitious set" and said that the album's cover version of [[Massive Attack]]'s "[[Teardrop (Massive Attack song)|Teardrop]]" was "an exquisite reworking".<ref name= "Denselow">{{cite web |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2012/feb/02/o-hooley-and-tido-the-fragile-review|title=O'Hooley & Tidow: The Fragile <U+2013> review |author= [[Robin Denselow]]|publisher= ''[[The Guardian]]''|date= 2 February 2012|accessdate=22 March 2012}}</ref> ''Guardian'' music critic [[Jude Rogers]] voted it as one of the best tracks of 2012.<ref name="Rogers">{{cite news | url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/musicblog/2012/dec/17/guardian-best-albums-2012-critics-individual-lists | title=The best albums of 2012: our critics' individual choices | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=17 December 2012 | accessdate=4 January 2013 | author=Jude Rogers and others | location=London}}</ref>

Spiral Earth's reviewer said that ''The Fragile'' was an "incredibly moving, deep and finely nuanced album".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spiralearth.co.uk/news/Review-story.asp?nid=5933 |title=The Fragile - O'Hooley & Tidow|publisher= Spiral Earth|date= 2 February 2012|accessdate= 25 June 2012}}</ref>''Northern Sky'' praised the album's "complex string arrangements and fine instrumental accompaniment" and "highly accomplished pieces of musical composition; you can never second guess what's around the corner in terms of sonic exploration".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allanwilkinson.co.uk/node/2073|title= Album Review: O'Hooley & Tidow - The Fragile (No Masters)|author= Allan Wilkinson|publisher= ''Northern Sky''|date= 12 February 2012|accessdate=18 May 2012}}</ref> Reviewing the album for Folking.com, Dai Jeffries said "The confidence, power and earthiness of their voices both solo and in harmony are what shine through this excellent album.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.folking.wordpress.com/2012/01/17/ohooley-tidow-the-fragile-no-masters-nmcd39/|title= O<U+2019>HOOLEY & TIDOW <U+2013> The Fragile <U+2013> NO MASTERS NMCD39|author= Dai Jeffries|publisher= Folking.com|date= 17 January 2012|accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> Folk Wales Online described the album as "breathtakingly original".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.folkwales.org.uk/Magazine/Sept%202012/CD%20Reviews.html|title= CD Reviews|author= Mick Tems|publisher= Folkwales Online Magazine|date= September 2012|accessdate=17 September 2012}}</ref> 

''Northern Sky'' music magazine's reviewer described the song "The Last Polar Bear" as "utterly beautiful", saying "This is how love songs should be written."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allanwilkinson.co.uk/node/2073|title= Single Review: O'Hooley & Tidow - The Last Polar Bear (Download)|author= Allan Wilkinson|publisher= ''Northern Sky''|date= 22 November 2011|accessdate=27 November 2011}}</ref>

==Cover artwork==
The illustrations on the album cover are by Kate Aughey.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kateaugheyillustrations.blogspot.co.uk/2012/01/more-from-ohooley-and-tidow-commission.html|title= More from the O'Hooley and Tidow Commission|publisher= Kate Aughey Illustrations|date= 10 January 2012 |accessdate= 24 June 2012}}</ref> The photographs of O<U+2019>Hooley & Tidow standing in the sea were taken by Casey Orr at [[Sandsend]] in [[Whitby]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ohooleyandtidow.com/the-fragile/|title=The Fragile|publisher= O'Hooley & Tidow website|year= 2012 |accessdate= 30 June 2012}}</ref>

